{{Infobox landform | name = Arctic Cape | other_name = {{lang|ru|Мыс Арктический}} | image = Arctic Cape.svg | image_size = 250px | caption = Location of Arctic Cape | map = Russia Krasnoyarsk Krai | map_width = | map_caption = | location = [[Krasnoyarsk Krai]], {{RUS}} | water_bodies =[[Arctic Ocean]] | coordinates = {{coord|81|16|15.8|N|95|47|4.7|E|type:landmark_region:RU_scale:1000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | elevation = | area = [[Russian Far North]] | references = }}
The '''Arctic Cape''' ({{lang-ru|Мыс Арктический}}, ''Mys Arkticheskiy'') is a [[headland]] in [[Severnaya Zemlya]], [[Russia]].<ref name="mapcartaA">{{cite web|url=http://mapcarta.com/15368460|title= Mys Arkticheskiy|work=Mapcarta|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref>
With a distance of 990.7&nbsp;km to the [[North Pole]], the Arctic Cape is sometimes used as starting point for expeditions to the [[North Pole]]. ==Geography== Stretching out towards the [[Arctic Ocean]] by the [[Molotov Glacier]],<ref name="mapcartaA"/> it is the northernmost point of [[Komsomolets Island]],<ref name="epf668"/> which in turn is the northernmost [[island]] of the archipelago. Under [[Joseph Stalin]] the cape was known as Cape [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]].<ref name="epf668"/>
The Arctic Cape is not the northernmost point of Russia. That distinction goes to [[Cape Fligely]] (mys Fligeli) on [[Rudolf Island]] (ostrov Rudolfa), an island in the [[Franz Josef Land]] archipelago. The northernmost point of mainland Asia is [[Cape Chelyuskin]].
This cape also marks the [[Kara Sea]]'s northeastern limit, which is the eastern end of a line running from [[Cape Kohlsaat]] in [[Franz Josef Land]] to the Arctic Cape. {| |- valign="top" |[[File: Kap Arktitscheski 1 2014-08-31.jpg|thumb|300px|Empty oil drums at Arctic Cape]] |}
==References== <references> <ref name="epf668">{{cite book|last= Mills|first=William James|title=Exploring Polar Frontiers: a Historical Encyclopedia|publisher=ABC-CLIO|date=December 2003|volume=2|pages=668|isbn=1-57607-422-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PYdBH4dOOM4C&pg=PA668&dq=komsomolets+island&num=30&as_brr=3&cd=3#v=onepage&q=komsomolets%20island&f=false|quote=Ushakov and his two companions explored the west coast of the large central island—October Revolution—before crossing a strait to Komsomolets Island and sledging to the northernmost point of the archipelago. This is now known as Arctic Cape, though Ushakov originally named it for the later disgraced politician Vyechyslav Molotov.}}</ref> </references>
