{{For|the building in Mexico City|El Parián Commercial Passage}}
'''Pariáns''' were districts of cities in the [[Philippines]] during the country's [[History of the Philippines (1521–1898)|Spanish colonial era]] where [[Chinese people|Chinese]] were required to live by Spanish colonial authorities. In Luzon there are several towns and cities with district for chinese settlers, the most famous is the [[Parián (Manila)|parian]] of Manila, other is Vigan and Malolos established in 1700s. Chinese enclave of Malolos were from migrants from Manila. In Visayas, [[Cebu City]]<ref name=NCCA>{{cite web|last=DELA CERNA|first=MADRILENA|title=Parian in Cebu|url=http://www.ncca.gov.ph/about-culture-and-arts/articles-on-c-n-a/article.php?igm=2&i=188|publisher=National Commission for Culture and the Arts|accessdate=21 February 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224131510/http://www.ncca.gov.ph/about-culture-and-arts/articles-on-c-n-a/article.php?igm=2&i=188|archivedate=24 February 2014|df=}}</ref>  and [[Iloilo City]] had also parians.  Cebu's parian was founded in 1590 after the arrival of Chinese traders and was supervised by the [[Jesuits]].<ref name=NCCA />  [[Molo, Iloilo City|Molo]] was the location of Iloilo's parian.

